.', 'Metabolism, Synergism', NULL, NULL, 'Moderate', NULL, 'DDInter', 'pharmacodynamic', NULL, 'https://ddinter2.scbdd.com/server/interact/164926/', '[1] Mills KC "Serotonin syndrome: A clinical update." Crit Care Clin 13 (1997): 763[2] "Product Information. Zomig (zolmitriptan)." Zeneca Pharmaceuticals, Wilmington, DE.[3] Sternbach H "The serotonin syndrome." Am J Psychiatry 148 (1991): 705-13[4] "Product Information. Eldepryl (selegiline)." Somerset Pharmaceuticals Inc, Tampa, FL.[5] Gardner DM, Lynd LD "Sumatriptan contraindications and the serotonin syndrome." Ann Pharmacother 32 (1998): 33-8[6] Boyer EW, Shannon M "The serotonin syndrome." N Engl J Med 352 (2005): 1112-20[7] Shapiro RE, Tepper SJ "The serotonin syndrome, triptans, and the potential for drug-drug interactions." Headache 47 (2007): 266-9[8] Nierenberg DW, Semprebon M "The central nervous system serotonin syndrome." Clin Pharmacol Ther 53 (1993): 84-8[9] Martin TG "Serotonin syndrome." Ann Emerg Med 28 (1996): 520-6[10] Mathew NT, Tietjen GE, Lucker C "Serotonin syndrome complicating migraine pharmacotherapy." Cephalalgia 16 (1996): 323-7[11] "Product Information. Zelapar (selegiline)." Valeant Pharmaceuticals, Costa Mesa, CA.[12] "Product Information. Emsam (selegiline)." Bristol-Myers Squibb, Princeton, NJ.[13] Ito D, Amano T, Sato H, Fukuuchi Y "Paroxysmal hypertensive crises induced by selegiline in a patient with Parkinson''s disease." J Neurol 248 (2001): 533-4[14] McGrath PJ, Stewart JW, Quitkin FM "A possible L-deprenyl induced hypertensive reaction." J Clin Psychopharmacol 9 (1989): 310-1[15] Zetin M, Plon L, DeAntonio M "MAOI reaction with powdered protein dietary supplement." J Clin Psychiatry 48 (1987): 499[16] Pohl R, Balon R, Berchou R "Reaction to chicken nuggets in a patient taking an MAOI." Am J Psychiatry 145 (1988): 651[17] Tailor SA, Shulman KI, Walker SE, Moss J, Gardner D "Hypertensive episode associated with phenelzine and tap beer--a reanalysis of the role of pressor amines